#* {{quote-journal|en|author=“Mustapha Rub-a-Dub Keli Khan” [pseudonym; {{w|Washington Irving}}; [[w:William Irving (New York)|William Irving]]; {{w|James Kirke Paulding}}]|title=Letter from Mustapha Rub-a-Dub Keli Khan, to Asem Hacchem, Principal Slave-driver to His Highness the Bashaw of Tripoli|magazine=[[w:Salmagundi (periodical)|Salmagundi; or, The Whim-whams and Opinions of Launcelot Langstaff, Esq. and Others [...] First Series. In Two Volumes]]|edition=new corrected|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=[[w:Harper (publisher)|Harper & Brothers]]{{nb...|82, Cliff-Street.}}|date=15 October 1807|year_published=1835|volume=II|issue=XVI|page=157|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=UasyAAAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PA157|oclc=191247659|passage=It is that fiend politics, Asem,—that baneful fiend, which '''bewildereth''' every brain, and poisons every social feeling; which intrudes itself at the festive banquet, and, like the detestable harpy, pollutes the very viands of the table; [...]}}
